Last minute: Our cosmic visitor is the giant asteroid 2014 JO25
There are billions, perhaps more, of giant asteroids in the solar system that are loose and could have serious consequences if they hit.
These objects, which may have closed or open orbits left over from the formation of the Sun, sometimes pass through Earth.
The 650-meter-wide asteroid 2014 JO25 is one such visitor and will pass 1.75 million kilometers from its closest point to Earth today at 2:24 p.m.
We're hearing more and more of this kind of news every day.
This is mainly due to the advances in observation techniques and instruments.
This allows us to identify smaller asteroids that have not been identified before.
For example, last January, an asteroid the size of a bus passed within about half the distance of the Earth and the Moon.
And even more interesting, the asteroid was detected just days before the transit.
So there could be other space buses coming our way right now.
Imagine if you were told that an asteroid 20 meters in diameter was going to hit the middle of your neighborhood.
Well, asteroids this size won't actually destroy your neighborhood, but they'll probably blow up the windows of all the buildings.
This will be due to the shock waves from the asteroid that will explode in the atmosphere.
For example, in 2013, an asteroid that hit Russia was this big and it was able to smash windows in several cities.
But if you have a neighborhood targeted by an asteroid 100 meters in diameter, I recommend that you go at least 30 miles away from your neighborhood.
Criteria such as the size of the asteroid and the angle of impact determine the depth of the impact crater and the damage caused by the impact.
Let's look at a few scenarios from the European Space Agency's simulation.
If an asteroid 100 meters in diameter were to hit the Earth at a 45-degree angle, at 60 kilometers per second, it would form a crater about 250 meters deep and 1,200 meters wide.
The impact is equivalent to a six-magnitude earthquake on the Richter scale, and even if you're 10 kilometers from the point of impact, you'll still get a third-degree burn.
And the others, 30 miles away, will be waiting for the shattered windows.
If an asteroid a mile across hits it, it's even more depressing.
If an asteroid of this size, with the same angle and velocity, were to hit Earth, it would form a crater about 2,000 feet deep and seven miles across.
So a whole neighborhood turns into a crater and disappears instantly.
The heat from the impact will cause a third-degree burn to your body even if you're 60 miles away from the point of impact.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage from the asteroid depends not only on the chemical composition of the asteroid but also on the rock structure of the area it will hit.
The above values are based on a scenario in which a hard rock-like asteroid crashes into a region of bulky rock.
If the asteroid is mostly iron, and it hits a surface that's formed by the cooling of lava, the crater will triple in size, and the resulting catastrophe will be doubled.
66 million years ago, something even worse happened to the dinosaurs, and they were devastated by an asteroid about 10 kilometers across.
The asteroid impact instantly wiped out 75% of all marine and terrestrial life.
If an asteroid this large to wipe out the dinosaurs were to hit Earth, the safest option would be to leave.
Tons of matter falling on Earth from space every day.
Most of it burns up in the atmosphere.
Some meteorites that are large enough burn up in the atmosphere, causing what is known among the public as starbursts.
Let's finish with another heartwarming story.
Studies show that an asteroid so massive that it would cause serious destruction is not expected to hit Earth for the next 300 to 400 years.
As creatures who live an average of 70 years, I'm sure you're a little relieved.
