Human rights group issued a travel advisory for Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a travel advisory for people of color to Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The State of Missouri NAACP Travel Advisory Notice, effective August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise special caution and exercise extreme caution when traveling across the state as noted therein due to recent suspicious, racially based incidents occurring throughout the state".
The NAACP said a new Missouri law made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, but that the state's law enforcement's disproportionate targeting of minorities was also effective in the group's issuance of this travel warning.
"There are human rights violations that happen to people.
They're being stopped, beaten and killed because of the color of their skin", Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We're hearing complaints at a rate we've never heard before".
This is the first time the association has issued such a warning for a state in the United States.
The group cited racist slurs against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders was detained by Missouri police earlier this year after running out of fuel while crossing the state, uncharged, and died under suspicious circumstances.
The advisory also points to a new report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office that shows black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
Chapel said the advisory is "to alert people and warn their families, friends and coworkers about what could happen in Missouri".
"People should be prepared to bring bail money with them, "to inform their relatives that they are going to pass through this state".
