There's no public transportation.
The town of 19,000 includes wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, wrinkled iron roofs turned to various yellowish-brown tones by rust.
Let alone journalists, very few Indonesians have traveled here and almost no foreigners have traveled here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, referring to her brightly colored, hand-touched yellow, dark shirt and bright skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies".
Papua is the poorest region in Indonesia, with 28 percent of the population living below the poverty line and the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's golden land.
Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous region the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper from here.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion worth of timber reserves.
Yet, these wealthy people, a source of poverty for the Papuans, maintain a stifling presence of Indonesia's powerful military.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reports that Freeport paid out about $20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including amounts up to $150,000 given to a single officer.
The Papuans' call for more autonomy threatens this golden egg-laying hen and is ruthlessly violating their rights.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned.
Mass killings in the mountainous areas of Papua in the 1970s have reached genocide proportions, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region last year alone.
The 2016 report of the Archdiocese of Brisbane, "We'll Lose Everything", includes testimonies from the poor, including unlawful executions, torture (among other reports, rape and electrocution are particularly popular), and the brutal suppression of peaceful protests, which took place the previous year.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week", says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
Pressure was increased as Papua's resources brought settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
The region's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim immigrants from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi come for economic reasons.
Javanese warung buffets sell gado-gado served with fried chicken and a peanut sauce mixed with vegetables.
The locals are having a hard time competing.
"The migrants sell chicken and vegetables at cheaper prices than the local Papuans in traditional markets", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the regional capital Jayapura for work.
"This has caused the indigenous Papuans, the Papuans mama-mama (women) to lose market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, promised to address inequality and rights violations in Papua during the 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, took the game to 27 of Papua's 29 regions, including Panaia.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the local people feel betrayed.
"We are heartbroken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi in the expectation that he would fulfill our hope that justice would be restored", You says.
In fact, Paniai experienced his worst just two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children singing Christmas carols outside a bonfire in Enarotali were overtaken by two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles.
The frightened kids told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers resented their style and later returned with four soldiers, according to local priest Javed Tebai.
Victims and witnesses said he chased a group of soldiers intoxicated and beat them with the barrels of his rifles.
Then one of the soldiers fired on the group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire, and the next day, the situation escalated.
About 1,000 Papuans men, women and children gathered on a football field outside the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita (running in a ring and mimicking the song of birds) of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua.
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police and military garrison.
As tensions grew, the soldiers were told by internal radio: "If the crowd resist more than three times, shoot them".
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the imminent danger and begged the crowd to return home.
No one was going to listen.
"When I turned around, I was shot in my left wrist", he told TIME in the window of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but he says the bullet came from a collected military round.
"It was crowded, there were many shots fired", he adds.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the attacks, the native Alfius Youw was shot three times.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Yohan, who, like many Indonesians, was known by only one name, told TIME in a pessimistic tone.
"I saw her die... and I kissed her".
Papua Police Chief Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only "securing" the station because it was under attack.
Papua police spokesman Branch Director Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015: "When people threaten to kill us, we have to defend ourselves".
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many others were injured.
The news of the deaths did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Jokowi made an impassioned speech in Jayapura three weeks later, expressing his sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address historical abuses in Papua.
"I want this case solved immediately so it doesn't happen again".
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he had established a non-judicial mechanism for historic human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the violations were long ago.
Some in the '90s, some in the early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to resolving these violations, but there are processes we have to go through".
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto backtracked, saying there were no plans to set up a complaints mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It's all going to be settled by law".
Wiranto, who is accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" related to more than 1,000 deaths during East Timor's bloody independence vote in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had already been solved.
The families of the Paniai victims have been bitterly skeptical of such claims.
"I have been interviewed four times in the past three years, but without any progress", says Yohan.
"I'm tired of it".
He says he's still living in fear years later.
"I'm scared", he says.
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the soldiers, I'm afraid of being shot".
His brother Yacobus echoes the view that the people of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the soldier after helping bury four of the victims.
"After I buried the bodies, the soldier came looking for me", he says.
The attacks haven't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police opened fire on villagers in the village of Deiyai, Paniai's neighbor.
During the clash between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to help take an unconscious man to the hospital, one person died and 17 others, including children, were injured.
Ravianus Douw, 24, drowned in a nearby lake while fishing, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's construction office.
Police say villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded with warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd, killing one.
Dominggu Badii, 29, who lived near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being treated, told TIME: "We were so panicked, we were afraid of retaliation".
"I've been hiding in my house for two days".
The Deiyai parliament called for the officials involved to be held accountable and the mobile police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problematic area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is fueling the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live scattered throughout Papua's green mountainous centre.
Many joined the rebel army, the Free Papua Movement (OPM), which claimed to protect the rights of Papuans by carrying out random attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some senior OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya, are from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai were arrested and held arbitrarily by the military in recent years under the guise of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some never seen again.
Among the Papuan people, Paniai is known as "a tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds discontent.
The little rice on sale in Enarotali is too expensive for the natives to buy.
The bread is not available.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly nuts, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the job of women who can sustain four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, selling the rest at the local market.
10 bills are only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities grew between the indigenous Papuans and the new immigrants who arrived in greater numbers since the opening of new air routes to Nabire Airport.
The jobs that are already scarce often go to immigrants who are better educated and wealthier.
It is rare for Papuans to have the capital or skills to run their own businesses competitively.
"Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there is no work or money", says John Gobai, president of the Panai tribal council.
The isolation keeps the world's eyes off Papua.
In addition, there are strict reporting restrictions for international media.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant institutions" despite being rarely allowed to film.
According to Phelim Kine, Deputy Director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi's election campaign promises to lift restrictions on news coverage and increase transparency were not fulfilled.
In a statement, he said: "For foreign journalists trying to report from Indonesia's troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua, there are new dangers: visa denial and blacklisting".
The lack of media control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands) urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "the wide-ranging and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Panaia attacks.
The same countries have historically supported the OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir ignored the group's claims, telling reporters in Jakarta, "The democratic system in Indonesia is still in place and there is a free media, so it is difficult to cover up the evidence in human rights cases".
The locals want more foreign government involvement.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the country's human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local residents broke their silence with pleas of "We want freedom", according to a source who attended the meeting and did not want to be named.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say it's unlikely they'll vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a well-meaning person, but he is surrounded by people who are involved in the Paniai attack", says tribal council president Gobai.
Jokowi wants the people of Paniai to know that they are in dire need of scant education and health services, besides living under the imminent threat of a tyrannical soldier.
Gobai says that like other Papuans, the people of Paniai see their vote as a "debt" they owe Jokowi to pay back.
"They don't need money, they just want justice".
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai attack carried out one last symbolic act of resistance: burying the body of one victim on the land directly across from the police and military station.
They will at least ensure that those responsible do not forget their crimes, knowing that justice can never be served.
"A member of our family has been killed", says Yacobus, his head bowed forward.
"What else can we do?"
Fire has engulfed Dubai's Torch skyscraper for the second time
A fire in Dubai on Friday engulfed the world's tallest residential towers, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-meter-tall 79-story building.
This is the second major fire to spread rapidly to the high rise building called the Torch Tower in two years.
The building was evacuated, no injuries were reported, and no explanation was given as to the cause of the massive fire.
"We were sleeping and we woke up to the fire alarm, people were screaming.
We ran down the stairs and it took us about 10 minutes to get to the 50th floor", a resident who identified himself as George told Reuters.
Dubai's civil defense authorities said firefighters extinguished the large fire around 4am local time (00:00 GMT) and were cooling the building.
The government has announced that they are trying to provide shelter for those affected.
This incident may raise questions about the safety of materials used in the exterior of high-rise buildings around the world.
The Torch Management's investigation following the 2015 fire found that most of the damage was to the cladding, which is the outer panels used for decoration and insulation.
In the United Kingdom, police said they believed the insulation and cladding panel system on London's Grenfell Tower, where 80 people died, may have contributed to the rapid spread of the fire there in June.
'Social assistance' to more than 4 thousand chronic patients
The Social Policy and Family Ministry has announced that the social assistance program will be launched for poor citizens and their families who are struggling with chronic diseases.
The Ministry, which plans to provide monthly support to patients over two-thirds of the minimum wage through the assistance program, will also provide regular psychosocial support.
According to the information received, the details and implementation principles of the "New Social Assistance Program for Families Struggling with Chronic Diseases" that began its work a while ago with the instruction of the Minister of Family and Social Policies Fatma Betul Sayan Kaya were revealed.
The social assistance program, which was launched in cooperation with the Ministry of Health to support citizens who are struggling with chronic diseases and are experiencing economic and psychological challenges, is in many respects the first in the world.
The Ministry, which has completed all the necessary preparations for the launch of the program, will provide families with not only cash but also regular psychosocial support through the social assistance program.
The aim is to ensure that poor citizens with chronic diseases and their families who continue their treatment processes at home are not left alone both financially and spiritually.
According to the studies, in the first phase, poor citizens battling with Sub-Acute Sclerosing Panencephalitis (SSPE), a brain disease caused by tuberculosis and measles microbes, will be given regular psychosocial and cash support under the new social assistance program.
In the later stages of the program, it will be extended to help poor citizens who are struggling with other rare and high-risk diseases.
In addition to the allowance, which is planned to be more than two thirds of the minimum wage, additional payments may be made to tuberculosis patients who are unable to pay for their own medical care, are bedridden or who are in need of home improvement.
To qualify for the allowance, the household's per capita income must be less than two thirds of the net monthly minimum wage.
In addition, citizens with SSPE should have a health board report prepared according to the procedures and principles specified in the "Regulation on Measurement, Classification and Health Board Reports to Disabled Persons".
