EPA Chairman Pruitt has stopped delaying Obama-era emissions-reduction laws.
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency Chairman Scott Pruitt reversed a previous decision to delay implementation of Obama-era laws that reduced air pollution emissions that cause dirty smoke.
Pruitt represented change by making his organization more responsive to the needs of state environmental regulators than past administrations.
He never mentioned a legal challenge to his previous position in a federal high court.
The issue is whether the states will begin meeting the 2015 deadline for ground level ozone standards on October 1.
Pruitt had announced in June that he would delay compliance by a year to give his organization more time to work on the plan and to avoid "interfering with local decisions or impeding economic growth".
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump, had long served as a reliable ally against tighter environmental regulations.
Since Pruitt came to Washington, he has repeatedly moved to block or delay regulations that the chemical and fossil fuel industries oppose.
Wednesday's sudden change is the latest legal defeat for Pruitt's agenda to reverse the regulation.
Last month, a federal grand jury in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator's attempt to delay the implementation of an Obama administration law requiring oil and gas companies to regulate and reduce methane leaks was overstepping the limits of his authority.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that the reversal in ozone standards only reinforces EPA's commitment to meeting the new standards on time with states and working through complex processes.
Pruitt, who has sued the EPA more than a dozen times in his previous work, said: "Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines for decisions, waited to be sued by activist groups and others, and agreed to settle the dispute to set timelines for decisions".
"We don't believe in regulation by litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take the law and the authority it gives us seriously".
Still, the EPA's statement noted that Pruitt could use his "power of attorney and all other legally available authority" once again at some point to ensure that regulations are "backed by sound policies and the best available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a wider rewrite of the ozone laws.
A bill passed by the legislature last month seeks to delay the implementation of 2015 laws by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been brought to the Senate for a vote.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
Schneiderman said, "The EPA's decision to reverse our lawsuits is a significant gain for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and the more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the dirty smoke that flows into their communities".
The case was brought to New York from California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is produced when general pollutants are released into the atmosphere by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources that react to sunlight.
The resulting dirty smoke can cause serious respiratory problems in a rapidly affected group of people and contributes to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists applauded Pruitt's surprise reversal of decision.
Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity said: "It is disturbing that so much pressure has to be put on the person responsible for protecting the air we breathe to get this sensible step".
"We must continue to fight against the Trump administration's ideological struggle to pander to environmental polluters and interest groups".
Inflation is one digit
Turkey, which recorded the largest increase in exports in six years in July, brought unemployment to 10.5 percent in April, which was 13 percent in January, and the economic confidence index rose to a 3.5 year high, and inflation dropped to one digit.
According to the data released by the Turkish Statistical Agency (TÜİK) yesterday, the Consumer Price Index (TÜFE) rose 0.15 percent in July, while annual inflation fell to one house for the first time since January at 9.79 percent.
In terms of the main spending groups, in July, the highest increase on a monthly basis was seen in the restaurant and hotel group with 1.75 percent, while the group that showed the greatest decline was clothing and footwear with 3.51 percent.
The highest year-on-year increase was in the transportation group, at 15.24 percent.
"The moderate pace of inflation is affected by the fall in food and clothing prices", Business Investment Economist Muammer Kömürcüoğlu said, noting that inflation fell to one house in July, in line with expectations.
But the core indicators are up from the previous month, contrary to the headline.
"We don't expect a relaxation in the central bank's tough stance", he said.
Headline inflation declined, but core inflation indicators rose.
The B index of the special comprehensive TUEF indicators, which the Central Bank also closely monitors, rose from 9.07 percent to 9.46 percent in July, while the C index rose from 9.20 percent to 9.60 percent.
Enver Erkan, Deputy Research Director of Kapital FX, said that inflation could be closed at 9.3 percent this year.
"The opportunity may pass to the Central Bank as of the first months of 2018", he explained.
Deputy Prime Minister Mehmet Şimşek: Inflation will close the year with one digit.
The central bank's tightening will continue until inflation drops below 7 percent.
We'll finalize the reforms at the nearby Food Committee.
Economy Minister Nihat Zeybekci: We are happy that inflation has fallen to single digits, but it needs to be permanent.
In order to combat inflation, food prices must be reduced and supplies increased.
Development Minister Lütfi Elvan: In the coming months, the annual inflation may be upwardly trending due to the base effect, but from the first months of 2018, the decline in inflation will be evident.
We predict annual inflation will fall even lower.
