Moore's Ford Massacre: Activists call for justice by reviving the racist lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury was driven through a crowd in rural Monroe, Georgia, and hurtled toward the small Ford Bridge in Moore.
The car, with four black passengers and a white driver, was blocked before it reached the bridge by a group of armed white men.
The leader of the gang, a middle-aged man in a thinly striped suit, took a long breath from his cigar and carefully peered in through the windshield.
Inside, the people were terrified.
"We want that shit, Roger!" he yelled.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams were heard through the darkness as a young black man was dragged from the front passenger seat.
Fortunately, this horrific scene from June 22 is only a reenactment.
But when a slap was thrown around "Roger"'s neck, almost everyone in the audience sighed in a very realistic way.
Since 2005, human rights activists have returned to Ford Bridge in Moore to reenact the lynching of two black couples (Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murray Dorsey) by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
So far, no one's been charged with the murders.
Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the revival, said: "It's unbelievable that even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are, not a single person has been arrested in all these years".
"It's a stain on history but a burden on our souls".
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia state congressman and a lifelong civil rights advocate.
For him, this revival is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the Monroe community that an injustice has never been corrected.
He said: "We want a lawsuit, we want a result, we want a healing, we want a reconciliation, but first we have to get justice".
"We can't have a healing and a reconciliation until we get justice".
The coroner is placing a sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Ford lynching in Moore on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding areas were suspected of lynching.
But not one of them was ever investigated.
Although the suspects remained on the run for decades, human rights advocates say the twin motivations of the lynchings were always well known throughout the town: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a high court ruling allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in a primary election later that summer.
According to the FBI, at about the same time as the election, black associate Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, during a fight apparently involving a woman.
Brooks said that the rumor in town was that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the baby she was carrying was not her husband's.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to get Malcolm out of prison.
Dorothy and her cousins, Mae Murray and George Dorsey, went to prison.
But as they drove away from the prison, they arrived at the Ford Bridge in Moore, and a lynch mob surrounded the car.
An FBI report concludes, "It appears that Harrison arranged and ordered the murders".
"It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and local law enforcement "that not only participated in the murder, "but destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
Brooks was more concise.
He said, "This was a voting rights massacre".
"They were all killed to send a message to black people in this community: 'This is what will happen to you if you register and vote.'"
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has been directing the annual revival of the Ford Bridge lynchings in Moore.
Her performance is all about detail, remarkable, and based on a deep-seated form of racism that many believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch, and even harder to look away, but Greene says that's the point.
She said, "We don't want to talk about lynching because it confronts all of us with the ugliness inside us".
"But if you don't listen to me or what's happening to me, I can't have a relationship with you".
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day, about 30 actors (a dozen white and the rest black) packed a room and listened as Greene eagerly entered the well-rehearsed outlines of the play.
Wade Marbaugh is serving as assistant director on Greene.
For years, the President played the part of the Klansman, but he says the role never gets easier.
Marbaugh said, "I feel dirty because that's not me".
"But I think it's important to keep that past alive because we don't want to go back to that time".
Actors playing Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, were rehearsing their lines throughout the room.
The game begins when Malcolm shouts at Hester, who is very angry because he slept with his wife Dorothy, and pushes her.
"Z...i, get off my property!"
He's reacting to the rascony.
There's a bang.
And then everyone (at least the black actors) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
He asked Rascona, "What?!"
She was nervous, she was surprised.
Was I too harsh?
Greene said, "No", with a chuckle.
"I just don't think white people said sh... at the time".
One of the black players said, "Yes", and he threw a mixed stone.
"You have to press the R.
So the energy in the room changes and a kind of intimacy replaces the restlessness.
Everyone is dedicated to getting it right, not just for the sake of the game but also in memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time Rascona says the N-word, sharp and emphatic.
No one's laughing at all.
The resuscitation is ending violently and quickly.
There's screaming, gunfire, and then silence.
A woman in black, standing on the bodies of the actors, reads Billie Holiday's melancholy hymn "Strange Fruit".
One of the two words breaks her voice.
A hundred yards back, an average of four dozen spectators wiping sweat and tears from their eyes.
The audience is almost evenly split between black and white.
A couple came all the way from Ithaca, New York, most of them from down the road, to see the performance.
As Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the Malcolm and Dorsey cemeteries, they all endured the oppressive moisture of Georgia for nearly eight hours.
Up until this point, the murders had been an anecdote, but now standing in the same place as the lynch mob means the weather feels like a curse.
As the final notes of the song fade, Greene invites the crowd to approach and examine the bodies.
The children kneel on their hands, clutching at the fake blood and the still bodies, and whisper to each other.
A little boy mutters, as if to remind himself, "They're not really dead".
A few minutes later, Greene thanks the crowd and then he's gone.
Actors throw the lynch rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh in the suit, playing the president Klansman.
Nick Rascona hugs two of his fellow actors and tears well up in their arms, the emotional toll of the performance finally coming to him.
One of the women whispers, "It's okay".
