The return on the stock market in Istanbul for 8 months stood at 50 percent
The BIST 100 index continued its upward trend that began in December 2016 in July and moved upwards to the 8th month in a row.
The index thus gained 45.3 percent for the period, the first time it has increased for eight consecutive months since July 2007.
The BIST 100 index, which has outperformed the world's major stock exchanges including Germany, the US, Britain and Japan in its performance since the beginning of the year, did not leave the lead in July.
The BIST 100 index, which ended July with a 7.06 percent increase, was followed by the Dow Jones index in the United States with a 2.54 percent increase, and the FTSE 100 index in the United Kingdom with a 0.81 percent increase.
The DAX index in Almaty and the Nikkei index in Japan ended July with a loss.
As of January-July, the BIST 100 index has been shown to perform higher than both the major world stock exchanges and the emerging market stock exchanges.
This year, the BIST 100 index gained 37.6 percent, followed by the Dow Jones index with a 10.76 percent increase, the DAX index with a 5.55 percent gain, the Nikkei index with a 4.55 percent increase, and the FTSE 100 index with a 3.21 percent increase.
The MSCI EM index, which is an indicator of emerging markets, returned 23 percent.
The BIST 100 index has shown similar performance in the past.
The BIST 100 index, which last gained value for 8 consecutive months between December 2006 and July 2007, had increased by 38.3 percent in this period.
The BIST 100 index also completed eight consecutive months of gains between August 1996 and March 1997, and nine consecutive months between May 1997 and January 1998.
In a statement to the AA, Eren Can Umut, Director of Investment Research at Meksa, said that the BIST 100 index has been rising for 8 months, and since the beginning of the year, the rise has exceeded 37 percent.
Umut noted that the MSCI emerging markets (EM) index has risen by 23 percent, and even if we look at these ratios, there is a positive split.
The flow of funds to developing countries has been continuing since the beginning of the year.
Especially funds in the high yield search prefer countries with higher interest rates.
