New results of Sweden's refugee age assessment test released
The latest results of evaluation tests on refugees undergoing a new medical age assessment in Sweden found that more than 80 percent of the test subjects were over 18, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these tests.
Sweden's national forensic and pharmaceutical authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed to make age assessments more accurate during the asylum process, following criticism of the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) for its failure to assess the correct age of some refugees who claim to be underage.
To date, the Migrationsverket has sent 6880 cases for testing and the Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals Department has now released the results of a total of 2481 from the testing period from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
In 80 percent of cases (as of 2002) the judge ruled that the victim was 18 or older, and in 25 cases the Medical Examiner's Office ruled that the victim was "probably 18 or older".
In 432 cases, the result was that the person was "probably under 18".
Tests were only done in cases where the age of the person was suspected.
Johan Göransson from the Forensics and Pharmaceutical Department says the results are consistent with the past few months.
"We don't see a big difference in statistics from the last few months, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local.
The high rate of cases of people convicted over the age of 18 doesn't necessarily mean that refugees lie about their age.
In May, the department released the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases where "indicated subjects were 18 years of age or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of 581 reported cases, it found that 243 cases clearly declared that they had turned 18 this year.
The medical method of age assessment, which involves X-raying 20-year-old teeth and performing MRI scans of knee joints, then having them analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute who has also studied the biological maturity of humans, assessing whether they enter the age of puberty earlier or later than normal.
"I have reason to think about it, and I think that this is not the kind of measurement that should be used.
It's highly questionable to judge biological age in this way.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend to be".
However, Göransson of the Department of Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals defended the validity of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of a child being wrongly judged to be an adult is small.
The highest risk is for people under 18, in which case the risk is around 10 percent".
