The Bank of England is expected to announce interest rates will not change soon after it eased speculation that there would be a rise in slow economic growth and moving inflation.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would continue to be "slow" as household incomes shrink and they keep interest rates flat.
Decision-makers on the bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6 to 2 to keep interest rates at 0.25%, thus calling for a smaller increase this month after weakening support for growth from slow economic growth.
The bank cut growth forecasts to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 in its quarterly inflation report, warning that household incomes would continue to shrink as inflation is still expected to rise to close to 3% in the spring.
However, he signaled that interest rate increases were needed to curb Brexit-fueled inflation over the next few years, and said borrowing costs could continue to rise more than expected in financial markets.
Members also voted to withdraw part of the massive economic recovery package launched a year ago after Brexit.
The bank said it would end its Periodic Financing Plan, which provides cheap funding to banks, from next February but expects to provide an additional £15 billion (£115 billion in total) under the plan.
Minutes after the interest rate decision was made, the bank said: "The central estimate of the MPC is that the short-term slowdown in gross domestic product (GDP) is continuing as the contraction in real household incomes continues to weigh on consumption".
On interest rates, he stressed that "some tightening in monetary policy" might be necessary to ease inflation and would be "a little bit higher" than the market expected.
Markets are still forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stresses that any increase will be "step by step" and "limited".
According to May's forecasts, the bank's reduced growth forecasts for this year and next year are compared at 1.9 percent and 1.7 percent.
The bank maintains its forecast of 1.8 percent in 2018.
