The pound fell 0.5 percent to 1.31 US dollars and 0.4 percent to 1.11 euros.
The decision to not change came after recent growth figures, which were disappointing at 0.2% in the previous three months, eased expectations of a surge in growth, compared to 0.3% in the second quarter.
Growth will likely remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, but the bank expects it to start to pick up slightly towards the end of the year.
While the bank says the contraction will get worse before it gets better, the latest inflation report leaves little to rejoice for households hit by rising inflation and meager wage increases.
The bank said monetary policy would not "prevent a fall in earnings" over the next few years, but it expected wages to improve "substantially" by the end of its three-year forecast.
The stronger demand for British goods as a result of the weaker pound will support the economy by offsetting some of the declining consumer spending.
