The NHS is going to prescribe the controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
Following a Supreme Court battle over funding of the drug on the NHS, patients will be able to access 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk people by around 86 percent, will be made available to up to 10,000 people through a 3-year trial.
The Supreme Court's decision last year agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal's approval, saying the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite claims by local authorities that it was funding it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed as a 'new and serious intervention' by Simon Stevens, head of NHS England, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a 'tipping point'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to register, with more clinics joining in October and fully implemented across the UK by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a range of HIV medications that reduce the risk of contracting HIV before sex.
Trials have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that a person has enough of the drugs in their body to prevent HIV infection from taking hold.
These drugs can be taken daily or up to two hours before sex.
Those eligible for treatment are gay or bisexual men, transgender people and HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will select suitable participants from men, women, transgender individuals and people whose partners are not known to have HIV status controlled with an antiretroviral therapy.
People living in the UK and registered with a GP will also be able to register for potential participation at participating local sexual health clinics.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England has signed an agreement to supply the drugs this week through an international tender.
The trial was designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how PrEP is targeted, administered and administered on a large scale.
Mr. Stevens said: 'This new and serious intervention will contribute to the widespread and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in my thirty years of progress in solving one of mankind's major health problems.'
Deborah Gold, president of the National Aids Trust, said: 'This is a milestone in the fight against HIV.
If targeted correctly at those who need it and those at risk, PrEP has the potential to transform the HIV epidemic in the UK.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to a new and powerful tool, truly personally controlled and not open to a partner's negotiation, through this trial funded by the NHS in the UK, which will lead to the improvement of many lives.
We welcome this announcement.'
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'The priority now is to ensure that the trial is rolled out quickly across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
With the experimental drug PrEP now available, we're on track to protect the more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV".
Shadow public health minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'We welcome the start of the PrEP trial, and it has been delayed by months of delays and then government backing.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-altering infection.
The experiment will take us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now, it's important that this trial is available nationwide as soon as possible to protect people exposed to HIV and to move us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in our society.
