The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, but it's a terrible one.
Researchers now say the first findings of an incredible rhino-sized creature found by a Canadian miner are so well preserved that experts have identified it as the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs.
It was so well preserved that they could tell that the seal skin was reddish brown and had a 'troubled history.'
A report in Current Biology described it as "the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur breeds in the world".
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived from the mid-Cretaceous period, 110 million to 112 million years ago.
Its remarkable well-preservation has astounded researchers, who describe it as "truly magnificent".
The herbivorous armor is the best preserved fossil of its kind, according to reports in National Geographic.
It was discovered by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011, while digging the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that looked strange from the rock around him and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years digging up the wild animal from a 2,500-pound pile of dirt.
After so much intense work, the finished product is now ready to be unveiled.
Caleb Brown, lead author of the study and a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display, said: 'If you close your eyes a little, you can almost believe it's asleep.'
'It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur species, the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
Researchers have examined its skin and found that although it was covered in armor and resembled a walking tank, this herbivore probably faced a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and a protective technique known as counter-shading, which many modern animals use.
Experts suggest that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs, allowing it to blend in better with its surroundings and outrun its enemies.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the Nodozor family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers have now completed their work and named the wild animal Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of Mark Mitchell, a museum technician who was part of the team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly trying to uncover it.
The species' remarkable conservation has allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the seals and the body armor.
They discovered countershading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means the upper part of the creature is darker from below.
Although countershading is common, the findings are surprising because the size of the Borealopelta far exceeds the countershading animals alive today.
This means that the dinosaur was sufficiently oppressed and hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that it preferred to face evolution as a means of survival.
But the most modern animals that use counter-shading (e.g. deer, zebras or armadillos) are much smaller and much more prone to becoming prey, meaning this nodosaur has had a serious challenge to survive.
"So the powerful hunting of a heavily armored animal shows how dangerous dinosaur predators in the Cretaceous could be", Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the seals also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues to its life, including preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate for its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was swept out to sea, where it sank on its back to the ocean surface.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and probably rivers and oceans spread farther inland than they do now.
"Nodozor is really remarkable in that it is completely covered and protected with a striated skin, but also the original form of the animal is preserved in 3D", Brown said.
'The result is that the animal looks almost exactly the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don't need much imagination to reconstruct it; if you close your eyes a little, you might even believe it's almost asleep.'
The Cretaceous was when giant theropods, two-legged carnivorous dinosaurs, roamed the Earth.
