A fitting analogy: the artist uses Chelsea Manning's DNA to create portraits
In the middle of the room at the New York Friedman Gallery, there are many faces, white, black and brown, hanging over the cables in the ceiling, each with an almost indistinct resemblance to the other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from earplugs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning, a former intelligence analyst who is serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic messages through the WikiLeaks website, has reportedly sent his hair cut from Fort Leavenworth prison.
The new exhibition, which opens August 2, is called A Proper Similarity.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her discipline with expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a trans woman pardoned by Barack Obama three days before her term ends, and a prominent dissident.
By algorithmically analyzing DNA extracted from Manning and using what a person with this gene data might look like to create 30 portraits, Dewey-Hagborg revealed not only the tractability of DNA data (that there are many ways to mark it and the determinism inherent in interpretation) but also its identity through a strict, perhaps somewhat cerebral interpretation.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but openly identified as a woman as a teenager, was convicted of 20 felonies in 2013, including six under the Espionage Act, computer forgery and theft.
His image was suppressed by the prison, so that he had only one photograph: a sandy, black and white selfie of Manning, visibly agitated, sitting in the driver's seat, wearing a platinum yellow wig that was a nod to himself.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was enjoying a huge success with the release of his 2012 project, More Weird Sensations.
In this case, the artist created portraits by filtering DNA from forensic debris, such as cigarette butts and gum, to create a picture of what these people might look like.
Just then, he got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison and they wanted some kind of portrait that could accompany this writing", Dewey-Hagborg explained at the press release for the new exhibition.
And at the time, there was no way to visit, no way to take a picture, so they reached out to Chelsea and asked if she was interested in getting a DNA portrait.
The artist and his imprisoned inspiration became unexpected correspondents, exchanging many letters over a period of two years.
They even unveiled Repressed Dreams, a cartoon book illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, in which the president imagines a future in which Chelsea is pardoned and she can see the exhibition in person.
Obama's request for Manning's release a few days after the book was actually released was a happy coincidence that came after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas.
While Donald Trump is finding new, tweetable ways to fight government leakers and transgender soldiers and further fuel the sharp divisions he's asked to fix, there's something profound and powerful about this exhibit that's opening now.
When asked about the strange timing of all this, Dewey-Hagborg said, "Things happen for a reason".
An artist's statement written on the gallery wall, under which Manning's signature is in large sizes (the dot of the "i" in her surname is inserted with a heart), called for an end to "automatic discrimination" based on "gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the wall opposite is his mitochondrial DNA sequence: many C's, G's and A's written in pencil...
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides in the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey Hagborg wanted to show how amazingly similar we are all, at least as biological creatures.
"What I hope people will take away from this is that they don't care about who we are in our genome and how open to interpretation the genetic data is, how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Imitation Memories, is on display.
"DNA data can tell many different stories, and this is 30 of them".
The last piece in the exhibit, which is in one room, is a page from the aforementioned short comic book.
Here Manning is shown leaving the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a King Kong-style speaker.
"They win when they shut you up".
"So never shut up".
The artist from Philadelphia said, "This came directly from a letter he wrote me".
"My hair still tingles when I talk about it".
Manning has not yet personally seen the exhibit (as he has quite presciently dreamed from the comic book), but when he does, he will be greeted by masks with his own genetic imitations, gathered in the middle of the room like a group of protesters.
Like everything in the exhibit, the genetic haplogroups were written down in pencil to Manning's height, which was specially made.
Dewey-Hagborg said of portraits, "In the past I would put them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd".
"I wanted it to be seen as a collective movement, shaped by Chelsea, which was also the movement behind her liberation".
