Start-ups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee happiness at her e-commerce startup, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or worse, misleading.
Even though he was committed to anonymity, some employees didn't trust the process.
"There was never any consistency or objectivity", says Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a 75-person hair care e-commerce company in San Francisco.
He called out for help.
A new kind of HR startup is emerging to help companies understand how their employees feel.
These allow companies to produce and license software that specifically aims to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to conduct agile, selective surveys, target specific teams and demographics, provide employees with anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow employees to report a misconduct bypassing senior management and going directly to the board.
Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Glint, a Redwood City startup that measures employee engagement by software analytics companies, said, "You have tools that track your health like Strava and Fitbit, but where's your company's Fitbit?"
Errett says that using Glint, three years later, his employees have a better understanding of what they're thinking and feeling.
It provides a heat map that provides a look at which parts of the company receive the most complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, as well as providing quick surveys and optional surveys to specific teams, so that you can pinpoint the reasons for these.
Companies are beginning to realize that they need to be aware of their workplace culture to avoid becoming the next Uber, which has been in a scandal since Uber described a harassment environment in which those who openly speak their minds are punished in a blog post by a former employee.
For startups like Glint, this need for supervision means a very lucrative business opportunity.
According to financial technology insights website Let's Talk Payments, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth $118.7 billion by 2020.
Interest and activity in Denver Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies detect and prevent misconduct, grew amid Uber's defamation controversy earlier this year.
Convercent has about 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to perform personalized pulse surveys, collect real-time hidden responses, and produce heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous helpline where employees can report misconduct.
If the president is indicted, complaints go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Covercent, said, "The public court has taken over the regulators".
Quinlan said that if a company treats its employees badly or unethically, even if regulators don't step in, it could face costly consequences from consumer boycotts, employee injury or lawsuits.
With more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations, restaurant chain Ruby Tuesday has been using Convercent for more than a year to help its employees stay informed about policies and procedures and provide easy access to corporate headquarters.
In the past, when an employee wanted to report a problem, he had to find a phone number or an e-mail address for the company headquarters, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
Ruby Tuesday's chief legal counsel, James Vitrano, said these were mostly intimidating and uncomfortable experiences, not a good way to follow up on employee complaints.
But now, with the company using Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers who lived far from the office, city or state (such as discrimination, harassment or unfair pay practices) can be detected and resolved more quickly.
Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group, said: "I can approach this employment experience even more with a holistic, 360-degree perspective".
"We also protect our shareholders from business litigation".
After the collapse of accounting firm Arthur Andersen in 2002 over ethics violations stemming from the Enron scandal, companies took ethics, values and employee relations more seriously in 2002, Quinlan said.
But after "social media came into its own", companies realized they couldn't stop their dirty laundry from going viral.
"Before technology was used to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy", he said.
