Facebook is increasing story verification to fight fake news
Facebook will send more potential fake stories to third-party story verifiers and show their findings below the original post, the world's largest online social network said Thursday in an effort to combat so-called fake news.
The company said in a statement on its website that they would use updated machine learning to detect potential fraud and send them to story verifiers, which would potentially show story verification results below the original article.
Facebook has been criticized for being one of the main distribution points for what many believe to be fake news that influenced the 2016 US presidential election.
With French voters facing a flood of fake news ahead of the presidential election in May and Germany backing a plan to punish social media networks if they fail to quickly remove hateful posts ahead of the September election there, the issue has also become a major political headline in Europe.
In a separate statement on Thursday, Facebook said a test of the new story verification feature is being launched in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
Sara Su, Facebook's product manager for newsfeeds, said in a blog post: "In addition to seeing which stories are being discussed by third-party story verifiers, people want more sources about what they read and share to make informed decisions".
He added that Facebook would continue to test the "relevant article" feature and work on other changes to the news feed to reduce fake news.
Comic book making: the story of a castle in England
In the recent past, the tiny Scotney Castle was featured in a Squeeze music video and was a haven for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But now, inspired by a comic by Jamie Rhodes, a broom-haired Yorkshireman with a passion for historical documentation, Scotney has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his comfortable chair in the Bewl River valley in Kent.
"I find it very beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years", he says, with a hint of a smile.
"What a personal bond it is to hold this letter in my hand".
A Castle in England, which spans from the Edwardian era to the Middle Ages, documents families living in Scotney, each story being painted by a different artist named from the United Kingdom (Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg).
This is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: she also wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a project she found unexpectedly emotional, inspired by stories in the British Library.
"I even got my eye on a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for King James supporters", he says.
"That was her thumbprint!
And letters always smell like business because back then you would light a fire for light.
For someone 300 years in the future, that smell feels like he's there.
Oh, I love the archives!"
As a lover of old papers, it seems too good to be supported by the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and to be able to stay in a castle for almost four months ("I'm a little overstaying my welcome, to be honest".)
Rhodes spent his days exploring the "new" Victorian castle, sifting through the archives and studying its many treasures and antiques, such as the heron heads mounted on the walls of the mansion and bottles that had been in the ditches for centuries.
He toured the grounds and ruins of the ancient castle, talking to guards, gardeners, and sometimes artists who worked on his book's illustrations.
Then at night, he would "drink whiskey and write".
The National Trust only gained full access when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died in 2006, so the detailed history of Scotney is relatively unknown.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only just begun to handle the archive, which he describes as: "For centuries the aristocrats were saying, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, maps that delineated who owned what: "You'd think land disputes would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a fir tree that two families fought over.
Forget about it, guys!"
Some of the stories in the collection, including The Labourer, which leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt in 1381, use the castle as a springboard for a broader entry into English history.
"In this book, the Knights of Kent and Sussex, there is a record of a rebellion at the castle in 1380", says Rhodes.
"The Peasant Revolt had started around here, and I thought a revolt would be a good place to start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the castle's history, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family hiding a Jesuit priest for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, featuring the 18th-century smuggler Arthut Darrell, who is thought to have filled a coffin with stones and embalmed his own body.
The Darrells, Rhodes' favorite Scotney family: "These gentlemen looked like pretty crooks, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved debt crises by marrying wealthy older women, whom I imagine as a bunch of handsome men with the knack of courting female heirs".
Rhodes, who's finished his tour of duty at the fort, is looking for another single-writing experience.
In the Finnish wildlife, he completed a two-week job on a comic about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium in the early 20th century, which has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney holds a special place in his heart.
