Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate IBS
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare to your digestive system.
But a new study suggests the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based protein and dairy products may help alleviate symptoms in those with inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable health condition, which affects 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are often advised to skip meat and dairy products to relieve their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the main amino acid in protein, tryptophan, helps to develop immune cells that develop a resilient gut.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna said that immune cells patrol the intestines to keep germs from sneaking into the body.
The cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote resilience, protecting delicate tissue from damage.
If the balance shifts too much towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
In experiments, mice that carried a specific bacterium in their gut developed a type of immune cell that promoted resistance.
And the bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to trigger the emergence of cells.
"We have linked Lactobacillus reuteri, a bacterium that is part of the gut microbiome, to the development of a cell population that promotes resistance", said Professor Colonna.
The mice that had more tryptophan in their diet had more of these immune cells".
If the same thing happens in humans, he suggested that a diet rich in L. reuteri and tryptophan could develop a more resilient, less inflammatory gut environment.
While working on a type of immune cell that promotes endurance, postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of mice had these types of cells, but another group of the same species, kept in a different location, did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiome of the mice, in other words, the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
And they sequenced the DNA of the gut of the mice, and they found that the mice that had immune cells had six types of bacteria, but the mice that didn't have them lacked them.
Mice lacking a gut microbiome and not developing this type of immune cell were given L. reuteri and immune cells emerged, because they were treated in a sterile environment.
To understand how the bacteria affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in the fluid and then transferred small amounts of this fluid to immature immune cells from mice that were free of the bacteria.
The immune cells have turned into resistance-promoting cells.
The active ingredient, when purified from the liquid, turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when they halved the tryptophan levels, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan noted that humans have the same resistance-promoting cells as mice, and that many of us harbor L. reuteri in the gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop in humans as they do in mice, but disorders in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
He said: "The growth of these cells is probably something we want to encourage because these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of tryptophan in potentially L. reuteri-presenting cases cause this population to spread".
