The White House show cost taxpayers thousands
According to military records released to TIME, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter into the southern grasslands for an organization that promotes American manufacturing cost taxpayers a figure of up to $24,000.
When the president boarded, the green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One, was the focus of attention at the White House, where the organization was introducing American construction programs on July 17.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured the products manufactured in all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut, a yacht from Main, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift from Mississippi were on display side by side.
According to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House War Office requested the helicopter's presence with a separate order (also called FRAGO) just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the south lawn for "unusual" organization.
The commander of HMX-1 sent an email to the Marine Vice Commander of Aviation, his superior, the day before the organization, saying, "I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually high-visibility organization".
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive at the south lawn around 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event and remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m.
The note added that if the departure from the White House was delayed, a second flight crew would be required for the return flight due to duty time restrictions.
The unit security personnel were on the ground while the aircraft was stationed inside, while the original flight crew were on the helicopter during the organization.
The records provided to TIME do not indicate whether a second flight crew was ultimately necessary.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The records show that HMX-1 investigated whether the organization violated this condition.
The commander wrote, "One question we asked was whether he violated the Hatch Act, and we were told he did not".
"Looks like you're locked in", replied the Deputy Commander.
The Made in America organization is designated by the White House as an official organization and not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even official organizations have political overtones.
The chairman of the organization referred to the ongoing health care reform efforts in the Senate at the time and praised the efforts to rein in government regulation.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically advantageous purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents are supposed to use them to travel.
But it's unusual that they're only officially requested for a photo opportunity.
Trump gained attention in February when his presidential jet moved behind the scenes of the first campaign rally in Melbourne Florida, and his Twitter account was filled with messages about his predecessor's use of the presidential jet.
White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters said: "The White House is excited about the Made in America exhibit, which features products made by American workers from all 50 states using American materials".
The HMX-1 crew frequently makes training flights in the Washington area and rehearses on the south lawn to drop the President of the United States on the White House on a spot-shoot.
Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July when the HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
An official said the flight for the Made in America organization was part of the aircrew's training needs for the month.
The unit's helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day on "non-presidential support missions".
The White House says taxpayers aren't charged for any other tricks involved in the organization.
A spokesman for Sikorksky said his firm was not involved in arranging the helicopter's display on the south lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights and it is difficult to determine the exact cost incurred by the organization.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's VH-3D meet rate is $24,340 per flight hour.
Unit records show the aircraft's flight time from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico, Virginia, to the base in either direction was 30 minutes.
The White House claims the actual operating cost of the helicopter is well below that.
"It is very misleading to charge taxpayers based on estimates of the cost recovery rate", Walters said.
"These estimates include sunk costs included in personnel, maintenance and annual expenses".
According to a 2015 RAND study, the Department of Defense's cost recovery rates do not include personnel costs but include fuel, maintenance and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated using the helicopter for this organization.
Spicer said, "The idea here is to showcase what's being done in America this week".
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contributions to our national security, and I think hundreds, if not thousands, of people's jobs depend on it.
And I think we're all proud of the helicopters and other military equipment that many Americans, like most Americans, work tirelessly to make.
So it's obviously appropriate to bring it up".
It's unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter while circling the southern grasslands for the organization, but he stepped into the driver's seat of a fire truck.
